======================================================================
H_4 RELATIVE HOMOLOGY — WHY IS H_4(T,T\v) = 0?
======================================================================

--- Phase 1: b4 distribution for b3=1 tournaments ---

  n=7:
  n=7: 500 b3=1 tournaments, b4 dist: {0: 500}, 147.2s

  n=8:
  n=8: 500 b3=1 tournaments, b4 dist: {0: 500}, 526.1s

--- Phase 2: b4(T) and b4(T\v) for BAD vertices ---

  n=7:
  n=7: 200 b3=1 tours
    b4(T) dist: {0: 200}
    b4(T\v) for BAD v: {0: 143}

  n=8:
  n=8: 200 b3=1 tours
    b4(T) dist: {0: 200}
    b4(T\v) for BAD v: {0: 431}

======================================================================
INTERPRETATION:
  At n=7: b4(T)=0 for ALL b3=1 tours (seesaw).
  Also b4(T\v)=0 for all BAD vertices (n-1=6, b4 vanishes at n=6).
  So LES gives: 0 → H_4(T,T\v) → H_3(T\v) → H_3(T)
  And H_4(T,T\v) = ker(i_*) = 0 iff i_* injective.

  At n=8: b4(T) can be 1 when b3=1 (coexistence ~0.15%).
  And b4(T\v) can be nonzero at n=7 (Paley T_7 has b4=6).
  The LES becomes more complex with nonzero H_4 terms.
  rank(i_*)=0 means H_4(T,T\v)=1 even when b4(T)=b4(T\v)=0.

DONE.
